<div class="main-content">
    <div class="container">
        <section class="two-thirds">
            <p class="intro">Reconceptualising Rocks is a program designed in collaboration between Melbourne Museum, Deakin University and the University of Melbourne. The program connects pre-service teachers to scientists, contemporary science, and museum pedagogy practices for the learning and teaching of Earth Science.</p>
        </section>
        <div class="one-third">
            <p class="centered">Responds to ReMSTEP innovation</p>
            <div class="innovation-callout">
                <span>4</span>
                <p>Specialist Science and Technology Centre collaborations.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="container">        
        
        <section class="two-thirds">
            <h2>Why?</h2>

            <p>The Reconceptualising Rocks program responds to ReMSTEP Innovation 4 &mdash; Specialist Science and Technology Centre Collaborations,  providing an additional experience for pre-service teachers.</p>
            <p>The aim of the program is to improve the competence and confidence of the participating pre-service teachers in the teaching of Earth Science. The participants’ content and pedagogy knowledge is enhanced by connecting them to scientists, contemporary science and museum education practices.</p>
            <p>Melbourne Museum acts as a contextual setting for the project, providing expertise as a key communicator of science in Victoria and a contemporary site for learning.</p>
        </section>
            
        <section class="two-thirds">

            <h2>How?</h2>
            <p>The collaborative team developed a learning experience for pre-service teachers utilising a wide range of multi-disciplinary expertise: science education, museum-based pedagogies, curriculum development, educational design and contemporary geology research and scientific practice.</p>
            <p>The program was promoted to pre-service teachers through the Master of Teaching (Science) at the Melbourne Graduate School of Education and the Community Science Project unit at Deakin University. Subject coordinators were actively involved in planning and promoting of the program.</p>
            <p>Approximately 40 pre-service teachers participated in the program in 2015.</p>
            <p>The program included 2 days on-site at Melbourne Museum and a 1 day field trip to geologically rich sites in Victoria (Phillip Island in March and Hanging Rock State Park in July). Dermot Henry, Manager Natural Sciences Collections and Priscilla Gaff, Program Coordinator Life Sciences facilitated the on-site sessions and field trips.</p>
            <p>One of the highlights was the back of house tour at the museum, where pre-service teachers were able to hear from and engage with the curators and collection managers in small groups. There was also an opportunity to take photographs and film various collection specimens to use in research and assessment tasks.</p>
            <p>Another highlight was the field trip to explore the geology of Phillip Island and Hanging Rock State Park. Over a number of stops, the pre-service teachers got an opportunity to explore unique key geological principals of the locations, linking the knowledge they’ve acquired on site at the Museum to a context of a living breathing landscape.</p>
            <p>Throughout the program, pre-service teachers had an opportunity to expand their knowledge of geology and learning at the museum by having expert guidance and exploration sessions at the Dynamic Earth gallery, undertaking the Rocks-Camera-Action education program designed for Year 8 students and undertaking a number of group activities such as mind-mapping, production of digital resources for teaching, mini-lectures from the Museum staff and hands-on activities.</p>
        </section>
        
    </div>
    
    <div class="container">
        <section class="two-thirds">
            <h2>Program outline</h2>
            <p>The 2015 program was delivered to a combined group of pre-service teachers from both Deakin University and the University of Melbourne. The July program was delivered over four days, three half-day sessions at Melbourne Museum and a one day field trip.</p>
        </section>
    </div>
    
