                        <h3>Overview of the program and pre-service teacher projects</h3>
                        <p>The plan for the complete program was outlined, i.e. what the participants would be doing and what the expected outcomes and outputs would be.</p>
                        <p>The particpants were given time to ask questions, choose from a list of topics and generate intial ideas for their project.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="well">
                        <span>4</span>
                        <h3>Reasearch into current best practice of teaching geology</h3>
                        <p>Assoc Prof Peter Hubber of Deakin University provided an overview of current reseacrh into this topic.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="one-third">
                    <div class="well">
                        <span>5</span>
                        <h3>Why the museum?</h3>
                        <p>The museum staff provided an overview of the Museum in order to give an insight into the role of the Museum collection in contemporary scientific research.</p>
                        <p><strong>Priscilla Gaff</strong>, Program Coordinator – Life Sciences, discussed the Museum's purpose and its role in Science and Education, how the participants would contibute to the Museum educational outputs and how this linked to the goals of ReMSTEP.</p>
                        <p><strong>Dermot Henry</strong> – Manager Natural Science Collections, then gave an insight into the significance of the collection with his talk, <i>Why the geology focus: Old rocks – who needs them</i>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="container">
                <section class="seven-twelths">
                    <div class="well">
                        <span>6</span>            
                        <h3>What do you know?</h3>

                        <p>The participants undertook a mind-mapping exercise to establish their current knowledge of rocks and geology. They asked to observe a rock and incorporate what they notice into their mind map.</p>
                        <p>The AusVELS curriculum content description for Science / Level 8 / Science Understanding / Earth and space sciences was used a guide: <i>Sedimentary, igneous and metamorphic rocks contain minerals and are formed by processes that occur within Earth over a variety of timescales</i>.</p>
                        <p>The participants were then asked to discuss how they would use the mind-map approach in their own teaching.</p>
                        <p>Finally they were given more information about their rock.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
